אֲשֶׁר: The Hebrew word אֲשֶׁר can mean “that,” or “who.” 
- For example, אֲנִי שָׂמֵחַ *אֲשֶׁר* אַתָּה בָּא, _ani sameach *asher* atah bah_, I am happy *that* you came.
- Or, as in השם *אֲשֶׁר* קִדְּשָׁנוּ בְּמִצְוֹתָיו, _Hashem asher kiddishanu b’mitzvosav, “Hashem who sanctified us with his commandments.”
Jastrow:
> אֲשֶׁר (b. h.  √אש, cmp. next w. ; v. Ges. H. Dict. s. v., as to opinions on etymol.) [being,] who, which. Ber. 11ᵇ א׳ בחר וכ׳ who hast chosen us; a. v. fr. (in prayer formulas).—In Talm. mostly prefix-שֶׁ.
